{
  "case_id": "D2N132",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports back pain following a fall during a surprise birthday party, describing the injury as a twisting motion and subsequent impact with a staircase railing. He denies pain radiating down his legs. He reports some stiffness with rotation and reports no numbness or pain. He has a history of lumbar fusion. He is currently taking ibuprofen for anxiety and continues to take medication for anxiety. He reports experiencing more pain when lying flat and with twisting motions. He denies any pain shooting down his legs when lifted.\n\nO:\nThe patient underwent an X-ray which revealed no significant abnormalities or compression fractures, except for the previously placed lumbar fusion. Examination reveals no focal neurological deficits. Vital signs are within normal limits.\n\nA:\nThe patient's symptoms are consistent with a lower back strain, likely exacerbated by the original fusion and the recent injury. There is no evidence of nerve compression or radiculopathy.\n\nP:\nRescribe ibuprofen 800mg three times daily with food. Advise ice and heat alternating on the back. Encourage ambulation. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one week if symptoms do not improve or worsen. Order medications and procedures.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nBack pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Lee is a 40-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of back pain. She states she was at a birthday party and she ran her back into the railing of the staircase and twisted her back. She denies any pain radiating down her legs. Lying flat and twisting motions aggravate the pain. She is currently taking ibuprofen.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nIbuprofen.\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nAnxiety.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nLumbar fusion\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the back shows range of motion without pain. Straight leg raise is negative. Sensation is intact.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the lumbar spine show no obvious signs of acute fracture. Evidence of a prior lumbar fusion with hardware in good position.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nLumbar spine strain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and heat. She will continue with Motrin 800 mg 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me as needed.",
